But gods, and men, and booksellers refuse

To countenance a mediocre Muse.

As at a feast, strains dissonant and hoarse,

A nauseous sweetmeat, or an unguent coarse, Are odious—just because there is no call

To have such dainties for a feast at all—

So verse, whose aim and end is to delight, Will, if it miss persecfion, fail outright.
